# Building reusable UI components for {{APP_NAME}}

This app keeps UI **reusable and consistent** with the broader {{APP_NAME}} product family. Reusability covers
*properties* (color, spacing, sizing, typography) as much as widgets — a hardcoded `12`
or `Colors.green` is a leak that can't be re-themed and won't travel. Follow these rules
whenever you add or change UI.

## 1. Decide the layer (where the file goes)

| What you're building | Folder | Notes |
|----------------------|--------|-------|
| **Core atom** — generic, domain-free (button, field, dropdown, chip, banner, checkbox…) | `flutter-ui-kit` repo: `lib/src/components/` | Governed by that repo's own CLAUDE.md. Very rare for an app to contribute; promotion rule applies. |
| **Generic composition** — project-agnostic, built from atoms (responsive scaffold, toolbar…) | `flutter-ui-kit` repo: `lib/src/composite/` | Still no domain coupling. Governed by that repo's own CLAUDE.md. Promotion rule applies. |
| **Design token** — a reusable property (color, spacing, size, radius, typography, breakpoint) | `flutter-ui-kit` repo: `lib/src/theme/` | Extend existing token files in the kit itself. Governed by that repo's own CLAUDE.md. |
| **App-specific composite** — knows about {{APP_NAME}}'s domain/features/screens | this app: `lib/src/composite/` | Imports the external kit via git dependency; never the reverse. This skill governs app-specific composites here. |

**The test for "core atom vs. app composite":** could a totally unrelated Flutter app use
this widget unchanged? If it mentions {{APP_NAME}}-specific features, domain logic, or product concepts,
it's an app composite and belongs here — putting it in the kit would poison the kit's purity (rule 3).

## 2. Properties are tokens — never hardcode

Reach for an existing token first. The full catalog (verify against the kit's `lib/src/theme/`):

| Token | Where to find it | Notes |
|-------|------------------|-------|
| `UiSpacing` | `flutter-ui-kit/lib/src/theme/ui_spacing.dart` | spacing scale + gap widgets |
| `UiSizing` | `flutter-ui-kit/lib/src/theme/ui_sizing.dart` | control heights, icon/field/panel sizes |
| `UiRadius` | `flutter-ui-kit/lib/src/theme/ui_radius.dart` | corner radii (+ BorderRadius consts) |
| `UiColors` (via `context.uiColors`) | `flutter-ui-kit/lib/src/theme/ui_colors.dart` | semantic colors (success, warning, danger, info, neutral) |
| `UiTypography` | `flutter-ui-kit/lib/src/theme/ui_typography.dart` | text-theme builder + mono style |

Rules at the call site:
- **Sizes / spacing / radius:** a token, never a magic number (`12`, `280`, `BorderRadius.circular(8)`).
- **Colors:** `context.uiColors.<semantic>` or `Theme.of(context).colorScheme.*` — **never** `Colors.red`, `Colors.green.shade700`, or a raw `Color(0x…)` at a call site.
- **Text:** `Theme.of(context).textTheme.*`; `UiTypography.mono` for tabular/raw data.
- **Missing token?** Check if the kit should have it (see promotion rule, section 5). If not, add a local app-specific token in `lib/src/theme/` rather than hardcoding "just here" — the next call site will copy you.

### Gotcha: control height ≠ size tokens

The **rendered height** of Material-derived controls — `TextField`, `Dropdown`, `Checkbox`, dropdown menu-item rows, list tiles — is **not** driven by `UiSizing.*` / `UiSpacing.*`.
It is set by the **theme**: `InputDecorationTheme.contentPadding` (+ `constraints.minHeight`) for inputs, and `ThemeData.visualDensity` for menu rows / checkboxes / chips / tabs — all configured in the kit's `buildUiTheme()`.

**Editing a size token (or having a dead one) will not move these controls at all.**

- **To shrink/grow an input or menu row, change the theme (via app-side `UiTuning`), not a token.** See the kit's `Documentations/design-system-contract.md` for the full default-with-override pattern.
- **Verify the rendered result, not the constant.** A clean `flutter analyze` plus an edited token is *not* evidence the UI changed. Prove it: a `pumpWidget` + `tester.getSize(...)` height assertion or an eyeball in `flutter run`.
- **One shared control height.** All form controls — dropdown, text field, `UiButton`, chip, checkbox — must render at the **same height** (the kit's default, see `design-system-contract.md`'s setup section) so a row of mixed controls lines up.

### Semantic color the right way

Don't paint a widget with a literal color. Expose an enum and resolve it through `context.uiColors`, so the meaning is themeable and dark-mode-safe.

```dart
enum {{APP_NAME}}ThingTone { normal, success, danger }

Color? _toneColor(BuildContext context) {
  final colors = context.uiColors;
  return switch (tone) {
    {{APP_NAME}}ThingTone.normal => null, // let the theme decide
    {{APP_NAME}}ThingTone.success => colors.success,
    {{APP_NAME}}ThingTone.danger => colors.danger,
  };
}
```

## 3. Keep the external design system pure

The `flutter_ui_kit` (in a separate repo) depends **only on the Flutter SDK** — no domain logic, no app-specific concepts. That purity is what lets it travel to other projects. **This app must not add domain-specific edits to kit internals** — if a widget needs {{APP_NAME}}-knowledge, it's an *app-specific composite* that lives here under `lib/src/composite/`, not in the kit.

If you find yourself wanting to edit something inside `flutter-ui-kit/lib/`, stop and ask: does this belong in the kit (generic enough for any Flutter app?), or is it really a {{APP_NAME}}-specific composite or override?

## 4. Tablet-first (7" and 10" Android tablets)

- Targets 7" and 10" Android tablets. Interactive targets meet the **compact floor** (`UiSizing.touchTarget`, see the kit's docs for the current value).
- For layouts that must adapt, use `UiResponsive` / `UiBreakpoints` / `UiDeviceClass` (compact, medium, expanded, large).
- Hosts default the desktop window to **1280×800** (10" landscape, 16:10) with a **960×600** (7") minimum. Verify new UI reads well at both extremes.

See the kit's `Documentations/design-system-contract.md` and `Documentations/flutter-adaptive-ui-design-specification.md` for the full guidance on breakpoints and touch targets.

## 5. Promotion rule

Keep a widget **local** to {{CONSUMING_PACKAGE}} until a **second consuming app** needs it. (Example: a specialized {{APP_NAME}} card component stays here for now.) Don't generalize prematurely — a one-use "reusable" widget is just indirection.

**Promotion means opening a PR on the `flutter-ui-kit` repo** and updating this app's git dependency `ref:` tag once the kit is released.

## 6. Wire it up, then verify

1. **Export** the new widget from this app's barrel (if public):
   - App-specific composites → export from `{{CONSUMING_PACKAGE}}/lib/{{CONSUMING_PACKAGE}}.dart` (or wherever this app's public API lives).
2. **Test:** add a mirrored test (e.g. `my_card.dart` → `test/my_card_test.dart`).
3. **Analyze + test** — both clean before committing:
   - `flutter analyze && flutter test`

### Self-check before you call it done

Grep your new/changed UI files for the leaks the rules above forbid:

```sh
# raw colors (should be empty — use context.uiColors / colorScheme)
grep -nE "Colors\.[a-zA-Z]|Color\(0x" <files>
# bare BorderRadius / EdgeInsets numbers (prefer UiRadius.* / UiSpacing.*)
grep -nE "BorderRadius\.circular\(|EdgeInsets\.all\([0-9]" <files>
```

A surviving hit needs a reason. Otherwise replace it with the matching token.

## Component template (app-specific composite)

```dart
import 'package:flutter/material.dart';
import 'package:flutter_ui_kit/flutter_ui_kit.dart';

/// One-line purpose. Document the API and any variants.
class {{APP_NAME}}Thing extends StatelessWidget {
  const {{APP_NAME}}Thing({required this.label, this.onTap, super.key});

  final String label;
  final VoidCallback? onTap;

  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return Padding(
      padding: UiSpacing.allMd, // tokens from the kit, not magic numbers
      child: GestureDetector(
        onTap: onTap,
        child: Text(label), // colors via context.uiColors / colorScheme
      ),
    );
  }
}
```

**Kit components & tokens:** consult the `flutter-ui-kit` repo's [README.md](https://github.com/momomozakiki/flutter-ui-kit/blob/main/README.md) and [`Documentations/design-system-contract.md`](https://github.com/momomozakiki/flutter-ui-kit/blob/main/Documentations/design-system-contract.md).
